        "rich_text_R47Qty": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "The Subtle Detail That Makes All the Difference",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>The Subtle Detail That Makes All the Difference</h2><p>When it’s about the <a href=\"https://www.lucirajewelry.com/collections/engagement-rings\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Lab Grown Diamond Engagement Ring\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Engagement Ring</span></a>, we obviously focus on the big-picture details. The size and shape of the stone, the sparkle, and the overall style of the setting is all we care about. But there's one small detail that can have a surprisingly big impact on your ring’s beauty, security, and durability. We are talking about the prongs!</p><p>Also known as claws, prongs are the tiny metal arms that hold the diamond in place. While these tiny pieces may seem minor and insignificant in front of the brilliance of the center stone, the prongs can dramatically influence the overall look and longevity of your special ring. Let’s break down what you need to know to choose the perfect ones.</p>",
            "custom_id": ""
          }
        },
        "rich_text_cb4Myt": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "What Are Prongs in an Engagement Ring?",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>What Are Prongs in an Engagement Ring?</h2>",
            "custom_id": "prongs"
          }
        },
        "image_with_text_XNrg4h": {
          "type": "image_with_text",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/How_to_Choose_the_Perfect_Engagement_Ring_Prongs.png",
            "text": "<p>Prongs are the metal tips that hold the diamonds with a grip, usually from the widest part of the diamond, helping the diamond stay put and well-settled. Most of the classic <a href=\"https://www.lucirajewelry.com/collections/solitaire-rings\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Solitaire Diamond Rings\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Solitaire Rings</span></a> use either four or six prongs. However, the style of the prong and the number of tips may be altered depending on the shape of the Lab Grown Diamond and the design of the ring you’re looking for. The trick is finding the right balance between function and style. </p>",
            "reverse_layout": false,
            "custom_id": "",
            "image_size_option": "medium"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_34pWtm": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Number of Prongs: Four vs. Six (or More)",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Number of Prongs: Four vs. Six (or More)</h2><p>How many prongs your ring needs is the first thing to be considered, because the number of claws affects both the security and the aesthetics of the diamond. Now the question is to decide which one to go for: four, six, or more? Let’s find out!</p>",
            "custom_id": "number"
          }
        },
